            "id": "7919a639451c48749213f",
            "questionText": "A hydroelectric power plant generates AC power at $!$15\\ \\text{kV}$!$. This power is then stepped up using a transformer with $!$2500$!$ turns in its primary coil and $!$50000$!$ turns in its secondary coil for long-distance transmission. Before reaching residential areas, the high-voltage power passes through a step\u2010down transformer. This step\u2010down transformer has $!$100000$!$ turns in its primary coil and needs to reduce the voltage to $!$240\\ \\text{V}$!$ for household use. Assuming ideal transformers, calculate the number of turns required in the secondary coil of the step\u2010down transformer.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "6ce3be511dcb43539b394",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct relation between the voltages and the number of turns for an ideal transformer. Which of the following formulas represents this relationship?",
